events.description: The first recorded instance of the Catholic practice of perpetual Eucharistic adoration formally begins in Avignon, France.

events.html: • 1402 – Battle of Homildon Hill: An invading Scottish army under Murdoch Stewart, Duke of Albany and Archibald, Earl Douglas is decimated by a contingent of 500 English archers under the command of George, Earl of March and Henry Percy, 1st Earl of Northumberland.[6]

events.description: Flight of the Earls from Lough Swilly, Donegal, Ireland.
events.html: • 1607 – Flight of the Earls from Lough Swilly, Donegal, Ireland.[7]

events.description: Bishop Gore School, one of the oldest schools in Wales, is founded.
events.html: • 1682 – Bishop Gore School, one of the oldest schools in Wales, is founded.[8]

events.description: Morean War: the Battle of Kalamata ends in a Venetian victory over the forces of the Ottoman Empire under the Kapudan Pasha.
events.html: • 1685 – Morean War: the Battle of Kalamata ends in a Venetian victory over the forces of the Ottoman Empire under the Kapudan Pasha.[9]

events.description: Grand Master António Manoel de Vilhena lays down the first stone of Fort Manoel in Malta.
events.html: • 1723 – Grand Master António Manoel de Vilhena lays down the first stone of Fort Manoel in Malta.

events.description: George Frideric Handel completes his oratorio Messiah.
events.html: • 1741 – George Frideric Handel completes his oratorio Messiah.[10]

events.description: The British Empire adopts the Gregorian calendar, skipping eleven days (the previous day was September 2).
events.html: • 1752 – The British Empire adopts the Gregorian calendar, skipping eleven days (the previous day was September 2).

events.description: Seneca warriors defeat British forces at the Battle of Devil's Hole during Pontiac's War.
events.html: • 1763 – Seneca warriors defeat British forces at the Battle of Devil's Hole during Pontiac's War.

events.description: The Papal States lose Avignon to Revolutionary France.
events.html: • 1791 – The Papal States lose Avignon to Revolutionary France.

events.description: Finnish War: Russians defeat the Swedes at the Battle of Oravais.
events.html: • 1808 – Finnish War: Russians defeat the Swedes at the Battle of Oravais.

events.description: Napoleonic Wars: The French Grande Armée enters Moscow. The Fire of Moscow begins as soon as Russian troops leave the city.
events.html: • 1812 – Napoleonic Wars: The French Grande Armée enters Moscow. The Fire of Moscow begins as soon as Russian troops leave the city.

events.description: Battle of Baltimore: The poem Defence of Fort McHenry is written by Francis Scott Key. The poem is later used as the lyrics of The Star-Spangled Banner.
events.html: • 1814 – Battle of Baltimore: The poem Defence of Fort McHenry is written by Francis Scott Key. The poem is later used as the lyrics of The Star-Spangled Banner.

events.description: The Ottoman Empire signs the Treaty of Adrianople with Russia, thus ending the Russo-Turkish War.
events.html: • 1829 – The Ottoman Empire signs the Treaty of Adrianople with Russia, thus ending the Russo-Turkish War.

events.description: Jang Bahadur and his brothers massacre about 40 members of the Nepalese palace court.
events.html: • 1846 – Jang Bahadur and his brothers massacre about 40 members of the Nepalese palace court.

events.description: American Civil War: The Battle of South Mountain, part of the Maryland Campaign, is fought.
events.html: • 1862 – American Civil War: The Battle of South Mountain, part of the Maryland Campaign, is fought.

events.description: U.S. President William McKinley dies after being mortally wounded on September 6 by anarchist Leon Czolgosz and is succeeded by Vice President Theodore Roosevelt.
events.html: • 1901 – U.S. President William McKinley dies after being mortally wounded on September 6 by anarchist Leon Czolgosz and is succeeded by Vice President Theodore Roosevelt.

events.description: Russian Premier Pyotr Stolypin is shot by Dmitry Bogrov while attending a performance of Rimsky-Korsakov's The Tale of Tsar Saltan at the Kiev Opera House, in the presence of Tsar Nicholas II.
events.html: • 1911 – Russian Premier Pyotr Stolypin is shot by Dmitry Bogrov while attending a performance of Rimsky-Korsakov's The Tale of Tsar Saltan at the Kiev Opera House, in the presence of Tsar Nicholas II.[11]

events.description: HMAS AE1, the Royal Australian Navy's first submarine, is lost at sea with all hands near East New Britain, Papua New Guinea.
events.html: • 1914 – HMAS AE1, the Royal Australian Navy's first submarine, is lost at sea with all hands near East New Britain, Papua New Guinea.

events.description: The Russian Empire is formally replaced by the Russian Republic.
events.html: • 1917 – The Russian Empire is formally replaced by the Russian Republic.

events.description: Raoul Villain, who assassinated the French Socialist Jean Jaurès, is himself killed by Spanish Republicans in Ibiza.
events.html: • 1936 – Raoul Villain, who assassinated the French Socialist Jean Jaurès, is himself killed by Spanish Republicans in Ibiza.

events.description: World War II: The Estonian military boards the Polish submarine ORP Orzeł in Tallinn, sparking a diplomatic incident that the Soviet Union will later use to justify the annexation of Estonia.
events.html: • 1939 – World War II: The Estonian military boards the Polish submarine ORP Orzeł in Tallinn, sparking a diplomatic incident that the Soviet Union will later use to justify the annexation of Estonia.

events.description: Ip massacre: The Hungarian Army, supported by local Hungarians, kill 158 Romanian civilians in Ip, Sălaj, a village in Northern Transylvania, an act of ethnic cleansing.
events.html: • 1940 – Ip massacre: The Hungarian Army, supported by local Hungarians, kill 158 Romanian civilians in Ip, Sălaj, a village in Northern Transylvania, an act of ethnic cleansing.

events.description: World War II: The Wehrmacht starts a three-day retaliatory operation targeting several Greek villages in the region of Viannos, whose death toll would eventually exceed 500 persons.
events.html: • 1943 – World War II: The Wehrmacht starts a three-day retaliatory operation targeting several Greek villages in the region of Viannos, whose death toll would eventually exceed 500 persons.

events.description: World War II: Maastricht becomes the first Dutch city to be liberated by allied forces.
events.html: • 1944 – World War II: Maastricht becomes the first Dutch city to be liberated by allied forces.

events.description: The Indian Army captures the city of Aurangabad as part of Operation Polo.
events.html: • 1948 – The Indian Army captures the city of Aurangabad as part of Operation Polo.

events.description: In a top secret nuclear test, a Soviet Tu-4 bomber drops a 40 kiloton atomic weapon just north of Totskoye village.
events.html: • 1954 – In a top secret nuclear test, a Soviet Tu-4 bomber drops a 40 kiloton atomic weapon just north of Totskoye village.

events.description: The first two German post-war rockets, designed by the German engineer Ernst Mohr, reach the upper atmosphere.
events.html: • 1958 – The first two German post-war rockets, designed by the German engineer Ernst Mohr, reach the upper atmosphere.

events.description: The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) is founded.
events.html: • 1960 – The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) is founded.

events.html: • 1960 – Congo Crisis: Mobutu Sese Seko seizes power in a military coup, suspending parliament and the constitution.

events.description: The first American saint, Elizabeth Ann Seton, is canonized by Pope Paul VI.
events.html: • 1975 – The first American saint, Elizabeth Ann Seton, is canonized by Pope Paul VI.

events.html: • 1984 – Joe Kittinger becomes the first person to fly a gas balloon alone across the Atlantic Ocean.

events.html: • 1985 – Penang Bridge, the longest bridge in Malaysia, connecting the island of Penang to the mainland, opens to traffic.

events.description: The Standard Gravure shooting where Joseph T. Wesbecker, a 47-year-old pressman, killed eight people and injured 12 people at his former workplace, Standard Gravure, before committing suicide.
events.html: • 1989 – The Standard Gravure shooting where Joseph T. Wesbecker, a 47-year-old pressman, killed eight people and injured 12 people at his former workplace, Standard Gravure, before committing suicide.

events.html: • 1992 – The Constitutional Court of Bosnia and Herzegovina declares the breakaway Croatian Republic of Herzeg-Bosnia to be illegal.

events.html: • 1994 – The rest of the Major League Baseball season is canceled because of a strike.

events.html: • 1997 – Eighty-one killed as five bogies of the Ahmedabad–Howrah Express plunge into a river in Bilaspur district of Madhya Pradesh, India.

events.html: • 2000 – Microsoft releases Windows Me.

events.html: • 2003 – In a referendum, Estonia approves joining the European Union.
